  {
    "elementType": "p",
    "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:173873DE-9AF0-4D88-AD20-A28BA6B025F7\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">These temporary shutdowns may quickly translate into SME exits the longer the crisis persists. Compared to larger firms, SMEs have less liquidity from external financing or previous years’ profits from which to weather any shutdown or demand shock (see <span class=\"cross-reference\" data-reference-id=\"MPAuxiliaryObjectReference:FBFDB216-FF1A-42AF-9CEF-23293531A98E\"><span class=\"kind elementIndex\"><b>Figure 2</b></span></span>). SMEs on average are estimated to have liquidity to cover fixed costs for an average of 10 weeks, 3 weeks less than larger firms (<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:E8EA9C23-210F-4A60-9CE4-7E7960A49D5B\">Bosio et al., 2020</span>).</p>",
