  {
    "elementType": "p",
    "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:698609D9-AF93-4713-AC6C-D609BE21D3A6\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Similar patterns arise when examining the share of informal employment among workers – informal workers disproportionately work in countries and sectors more exposed to the crisis. Although not exclusive to small firms in developing countries, informal work is typical of smaller ventures and also disproportionately frequent in low-income households.<span class=\"footnote\" data-reference-id=\"MPFootnote:CB847999-733C-4048-B271-147ACC10DB72\">6</span> Country-sector combinations with 10% higher informality rates exhibit on average 2.5% higher economic risk from the pandemic (see <span class=\"cross-reference\" data-reference-id=\"MPAuxiliaryObjectReference:A38E9B9E-8F38-4944-BF7E-6084949FD0D4\"><span class=\"kind elementIndex\"><b>Figure 3</b></span></span>, panel B).</p>",
